.TH scale_what_if_resistance  22.14 "Fri Oct 06 02:12:27 2023" 
.SH Name \fBscale_what_if_resistance\fR \-  Scales resistance globally or in a region to determine how much resistance can be modified in a region to reduce the entire IR drop
.SH Syntax  \fBscale_what_if_resistance\fR   [-help]   -reset | {-net <netname>  {-global | -region <x1 y1 x2 y2> | -instance <instancename> | -cell <cellname> | -file <filename>}    [-scale value | -scale_ron {<R_ON_scale_factor> | R_OFF}]  [-auto_scale_adjacent_via_layers {true | false}]  [-layer {<layername>| all} ]  } 
.P Scales resistance globally or in a region to determine how much resistance can be modified in a region to reduce the entire IR drop. In designs with power switches, the scaling of resistance will be applied to always-on net as well as its switched nets in a given region. Currently, it is not possible to apply different scaling factors for always-on and switched nets. 
.SH Parameters    "\fB-auto_scale_adjacent_via_layers {true|false}\fR" Specifies to use auto via scaling for what-if resistance analysis. When scaling resistance on a specific metal layer, via resistance on the adjacent via layers are automatically scaled with the same scaling factor. The default value is true.  Use -auto_scale_adjacent_via_layers false to keep via resistances un-scaled.  "\fB-global | -region <x1 y1 x2 y2 |>-instance<instancename |>-cell<cellname |>-file <filename>   \fR" You must specify either -global, -region, -cell, -instance, or -file.
.RS  "*" 2 When the -global parameter is specified with the -scale parameter, it scales resistance by the specified value globally for a given layer. If the -global parameter is specified with the -scale_ron parameter, it scales the resistance value of all power switch cells globally for a given layer. This is the default.  "*" 2 When the -region parameter is specified with the -scale parameter, it scales the grid resistance in the specified region. If the region parameter is specified with the -scale_ron parameter, it scales the resistance of all power switch cells in the specified region. The default unit of x1 y1 x2 y2 is in database units.  "*" 2 The -instanceinstancename or -cell<cellname> parameter specifies to scale the internal resistors from the PGV for the specified instance or cell.  "*" 2 The -file <filename> parameter specifies a file containing the list of instances and cells that use the same scaling factor. The format of the file is:  CELL <cellname>  INSTANCE <instancename>
.RE   This is a required parameter. Default is -global.  The precedence for resistance scaling is as follows:
.RS  "*" 2 Instance  "*" 2 Cell  "*" 2 Region  "*" 2 Global
.RE   "\fB-help\fR" Outputs a brief description that includes the type and default information for each scale_what_if_resistance parameter.  For a detailed description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command man scale_what_if_resistance.  "\fB-layer <layername |>all  \fR" Specifies the layer name (LEF layer or technology layer) on which the scaling is performed. Multiple commands can be issued to scale resistance on multiple layers. You can specify the all argument to scale all the layers. When the all argument is used, the -auto_scale_adjacent_via_layer parameter is disabled.  This is a required parameter.  "\fB-net <netname>\fR" Scales resistance of the specified net in the domain which is being analyzed.  This is a required parameter.  "\fB-reset\fR" Resets all the previous scale_what_if_resistance command settings.  "\fB-scale <value>\fR" Specifies any value greater than 0. For example, a value of 0.5 will scale the resistance in half.  This is a required parameter.  "\fB-scale_ron {<R_ON_scale_factor> | R_OFF}\fR" Specifies the value used to scale the RON of the power-gate instance/cell. The default value is 1. You can also specify the  R_OFF(case insensitive) keyword to apply the off state power-gate resistance for the specified instance/cell. 
.SH Related Information
.RS  "*" 2 scale_what_if_capacitance  "*" 2 create_current_region   "*" 2 scale_what_if_current  "*" 2 "What-If Rail Analysis" in the Voltus IC Power Integrity Solution User Guide
.RE
.P
